devilwm is a fork of evilwm that adds built-in support for application launchers (defaulted to dmenu).
devilwm also changes the default keybind of the delete function from Ctrl+Alt+Escape to Ctrl+Alt+C because I find it impossible to believe someone would find it pleasant to stretch their fingers that far everytime they wanted to close a window.
To clarify, the ONLY changes this fork makes is adding support for launchers and changing the delete function's default bind to something more convenient.


devilwm(1)                  General Commands Manual                 devilwm(1)

NNAAMMEE
       devilwm—minimalist window manager for X11

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       ddeevviillwwmm [_O_P_T_I_O_N]…

DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN
       ddeevviillwwmm is a fork of eevviillwwmm that adds built-in launcher support,
       utilizing dmenu by default. eevviillwwmm is a minimalist window manager for
       the X Window System. It features plenty of reconfigurable mouse and
       keyboard controls while providing a clean display, uncluttered by less
       useful window furniture (like title bars).

OOPPTTIIOONNSS
       ----ddiissppllaayy _d_i_s_p_l_a_y
              specifies the X display to run on. Usually this can be inferred
              from the DDIISSPPLLAAYY environment variable.

       ----tteerrmm _t_e_r_m_p_r_o_g
              specifies an alternative program to run when spawning a new
              terminal (defaults to xterm, or x-terminal-emulator in Debian).
              Separate arguments with whitespace, and escape needed whitespace
              with a backslash. Remember that special characters will also
              need to be protected from the shell.

       ----llaauunncchheerr _l_a_u_n_c_h_e_r_p_r_o_g
              specifies an alternative program to run when spawning a new
              launcher (defaults to dmenu).

       ----ffnn _f_o_n_t_n_a_m_e
              specify a font to use when resizing or displaying window titles.

       ----ffgg _c_o_l_o_u_r
       ----ffcc _c_o_l_o_u_r
       ----bbgg _c_o_l_o_u_r
              frame colour of currently active, fixed active, and inactive
              windows respectively. Either specify an X11 colour name like
              ggoollddeennrroodd, or a hex triplet like ##DDAAAA552200.

       ----bbww _b_o_r_d_e_r_w_i_d_t_h
              width of window borders in pixels.

       ----ssnnaapp _d_i_s_t_a_n_c_e
              enable snap-to-border support. _d_i_s_t_a_n_c_e is the proximity in
              pixels to snap to.

       ----wwhhoolleessccrreeeenn
              ignore monitor geometry and use the whole screen dimensions.
              This is the old behaviour from before multi-monitor support was
              implemented, and may still be useful, eg when one large monitor
              is driven from multiple outputs.

       ----nnuummvvddeesskkss _v_a_l_u_e
              number of virtual desktops to provide. Defaults to 8. Any extras
              will only be accessible by pagers or using
              Control+Alt+(Left/Right).

       ----nnoossoolliiddddrraagg
              draw a window outline while moving or resizing.

       ----mmaasskk11 _m_o_d_i_f_i_e_r[+_m_o_d_i_f_i_e_r]…
       ----mmaasskk22 _m_o_d_i_f_i_e_r[+_m_o_d_i_f_i_e_r]…
       ----aallttmmaasskk _m_o_d_i_f_i_e_r[+_m_o_d_i_f_i_e_r]…
              override the default keyboard modifiers used to grab keys for
              window manager functionality.

              mmaasskk11 is used for most keyboard controls (default: control+alt),
              and mmaasskk22 is used for mouse button controls and cycling windows
              (default: alt). aallttmmaasskk is used to modify the behaviour of
              certain controls (default: shift). Modifiers may be separated
              with + signs. Valid modifiers are 'shift', 'control', 'alt',
              'mod1'…'mod5'.

       ----bbiinndd _k_e_y[+_m_o_d_i_f_i_e_r]…=[_f_u_n_c_t_i_o_n[,_f_l_a_g]…]
              bind a key pressed with specified modifiers to a window manager
              function. _k_e_y is an X11 keysym name, _m_o_d_i_f_i_e_r_s are as above, but
              may also include 'mask1', 'mask2' and 'altmask' to refer to the
              globally-configured combinations. See FUNCTIONS for a list of
              available functions and the flags they recognise. If _f_u_n_c_t_i_o_n is
              empty, a bind is removed.

       ----bbiinndd _b_u_t_t_o_n=[_f_u_n_c_t_i_o_n[,_f_l_a_g]…]
              bind a mouse button to a window manager function. While
              modifiers can be specified, they will be ignored; the button on
              its own will trigger if pressed within a window's frame, or with
              'mask2' held anywhere within a window. Function and flags is as
              with key binds above. Valid buttons are 'button1'…'button5'.

       ----aapppp _n_a_m_e_/_c_l_a_s_s
              match an application by instance name and class (for help in
              finding these, use the _x_p_r_o_p tool to extract the _W_M___C_L_A_S_S
              property).

              Subsequent ----ggeeoommeettrryy, ----ddoocckk, ----vvddeesskk and ----ffiixxeedd options will
              apply to this match.

       --gg, ----ggeeoommeettrryy _g_e_o_m_e_t_r_y
              apply a geometry (using a standard X geometry string) to
              applications matching the last ----aapppp.

       ----ddoocckk specify that application should be considered to be a dock, even
              if it lacks the appropriate property.

       --vv, ----vvddeesskk _v_d_e_s_k
              specify a default virtual desktop for applications matching the
              last ----aapppp. Note that virtual desktops are numbered from zero.

       --ff, ----ffiixxeedd
              specify that application is to start with a fixed client window.

       --hh, ----hheellpp
              show help

       --VV, ----vveerrssiioonn
              show program version

       ddeevviillwwmm will also read options, one per line, from a file called
       _._d_e_v_i_l_w_m_r_c in the user's home directory. Options listed in a
       configuration file should omit the leading dash(es). Options specified
       on the command line override those found in the configuration file.

UUSSAAGGEE
       In ddeevviillwwmm, the focus follows the mouse pointer, and focus is not lost
       if you stray onto the root window. The current window border is shaded
       gold (unless it is fixed, in which case blue), with other windows left
       as a dark grey.

       You can use the mouse to manipulate windows either by click/dragging
       the single-pixel border (easier when they align with a screen edge), or
       by holding down Alt and doing so anywhere in the window. The controls
       are:

       Button 1
              Move window.

       Button 2
              Resize window.

       Button 3
              Lower window.

       Most keyboard controls are used by holding down Control and Alt, then
       pressing a key. Available functions are:

       Return Spawn new terminal.

       Alt+P  Spawn launcher.

       C      Delete current window. Hold Shift as well to force kill a
              client.

       Insert Lower current window.

       H, J, K, L
              Move window left, down, up or right (16 pixels). Holding Shift
              resizes the window instead.

       Y, U, B, N
              Move window to the top-left, top-right, bottom-left or bottom-
              right of the current monitor.

       I      Show information about current window.

       Equals Maximise current window vertically on current monitor (toggle).
              Holding Shift toggles horizontal maximization.

       X      Maximise current window to current monitor (toggle).

       D      Toggle visible state of docks, eg pagers and launch bars.

       If compiled with virtual desktop support, these functions are also
       available:

       F      Fix or unfix current window. Fixed windows remain visible when
              you switch virtual desktop.

       1—8    Switch to specific virtual desktop (internally, desktops are
              numbered from zero, so this actually switches to desktops 0—7;
              this only becomes important if you use application matching).

       Left   Switch to next lower numbered virtual desktop.

       Right  Switch to next higher numbered virtual desktop.

       A      Switch to the previously selected virtual desktop.

       In addition to the above, Alt+Tab can be used to cycle through windows.

       To make ddeevviillwwmm reread its config, send a HUP signal to the process. To
       make it quit, kill it, ie send a TERM signal.

FFUUNNCCTTIIOONNSS
       The keyboard and mouse button controls can be configured with the
       ----bbiinndd option to a number of built-in functions. Typically, these
       functions respond to an additional set of flags that modify their
       behaviour.

       ddeelleettee Delete a window. This is the co-operative way of closing
              applications, as it sends the client a signal indicating that
              they should shut down.

       ddoocckk   When called with the ttooggggllee flag, toggles visibility of any
              window claiming to be a dock.

       ffiixx    With the ttooggggllee flag, toggle whether a window is fixed (visible
              on all virtual desktops) or not.

       iinnffoo   Shows extra information about the current window for as long as
              the key is held.

       kkiillll   Kill a window. A more forceful way of closing an application if
              it is not responding to delete requests.

       lloowweerr  Lower the current window.

       mmoovvee   When bound to a button, moves a window with the mouse.

              When bound to a key, if the rreellaattiivvee flag is specified, moves a
              window in the direction indicated by other flags: uupp, ddoowwnn, lleefftt
              or rriigghhtt. Without the rreellaattiivvee flag, moves a window in the
              direction specified by other flag to the edge of the monitor.

       nneexxtt   Cycle to the next window.

       rraaiissee

       Raises the current window.

       rreessiizzee When bound to a button, resizes a window with the mouse.

              When bound to a key, if the rreellaattiivvee flag is specified, modifies
              the width or height of the window as indicated by other flags:
              uupp (reduce height), ddoowwnn (increase height), lleefftt (reduce width)
              or rriigghhtt (increase width). If instead the ttooggggllee flag is
              specified, maximises along axes specified by other flags:
              hhoorriizzoonnttaall, vveerrttiiccaall or both.

       ssppaawwnn  Start a terminal.

       llaauunncchheerr
              Start the launcher.

       vvddeesskk  With the ttooggggllee flag specified, switch to the previously visible
              vdesk. With the rreellaattiivvee flag set, either increase vdesk number
              (with uupp flag) or decrease it (with ddoowwnn flag).

              If neither flag is specified, a numerical argument indicates
              which vdesk to switch to.

DDEEFFAAUULLTT BBIINNDDSS
       These are the default lists of modifiers, button and keyboard binds.
       The built-in binds use the globally-configurable modifier combinations
       'mask1', 'mask2' and 'altmask', making a sweeping change to a different
       modifier combination easy.

       Note that 'mod1' typically refers to the Alt key.

   MMooddiiffiieerrss
              mask1 control+mod1
              mask2 mod1
              altmask shift

   BBuuttttoonn bbiinnddss
              bind button1=move
              bind button2=resize
              bind button3=lower

   KKeeyybbooaarrdd bbiinnddss
              bind mask1+Return=spawn
              bind mod1+p=launcher
              bind mask1+c=delete
              bind mask1+altmask+c=kill
              bind mask1+Insert=lower
              bind mask1+KP_Insert=lower
              bind mask1+i=info
              bind mask2+Tab=next
              bind mask1+h=move,relative+left
              bind mask1+j=move,relative+down
              bind mask1+k=move,relative+up
              bind mask1+l=move,relative+right
              bind mask1+y=move,top+left
              bind mask1+u=move,top+right
              bind mask1+b=move,bottom+left
              bind mask1+n=move,bottom+right
              bind mask1+altmask+h=resize,relative+left
              bind mask1+altmask+j=resize,relative+down
              bind mask1+altmask+k=resize,relative+up
              bind mask1+altmask+l=resize,relative+right
              bind mask1+equal=resize,toggle+v
              bind mask1+altmask+equal=resize,toggle+h
              bind mask1+x=resize,toggle+v+h
              bind mask1+d=dock,toggle
              bind mask1+f=fix,toggle
              bind mask1+1=vdesk,0
              bind mask1+2=vdesk,1
              bind mask1+3=vdesk,2
              bind mask1+4=vdesk,3
              bind mask1+5=vdesk,4
              bind mask1+6=vdesk,5
              bind mask1+7=vdesk,6
              bind mask1+8=vdesk,7
              bind mask1+Left=vdesk,relative+down
              bind mask1+Right=vdesk,relative+up
              bind mask1+a=vdesk,toggle

